BKC Research Sprint - Spring 2024¶

Visualizing Boston's Urban Spaces Using Open Data¶

Group 5: Landmarks of Boston¶

Team Members: Justin Wei, Gemma Li, Kevin Hu and Krithika Balaraman

Exploratory Data Analysis and Visualization Drafts¶

Our Concept¶

The registered landmarks of Boston are well documented with justifications of why they earned landmarks status, when they were petitioned for and who petitioned for them. The reports date back to the early 1900s and paint a colorful picture of the history of the city, and dedicated residents who worked to preserve it.

On the flipside, the city also documents applications that were rejected, or petitions that still await landmark status. Some of these structures have been demolished during the wait.

Our vision is to create multi-dimensional views of the city of Boston, based on the wildly differing experiences of these different petitioners and landmarks.

Additionally, we invite the audience to share their meaningful places, which would become their very own landmarks of Boston.

⭐ Findings:

  • In General Information category, we will rely on st_num, st_name, and zipcode in order to locate the respective building on a map. There are 88 entries that are missing the street address information, so we will drop those entries.
  • In Uses category, there are over 100 entries has missing values in building_typology and building_subtypology, which are the "General building typology classification" and "Building typology classification including subtypology based on building age". We have not decided what to do with this pair of features, so we are keeping these entries for now.
  • In Other category, only land_sf has no missing data; all other attributes have great missingness and are mostly unuseable. We may consider only keeping the "Land area of parcel (square feet)" and dropping all other columns.
  • in Building age category, yr_built is a key attribute we will be using for our visualization. There are 140 entries are missing "Year built" so we will have to drop those entries.
  • in Building size, Height, Number of buildings, Number of units categories, there are a few entries missing sqft, sqft_class, num_floors, num_bldgs, units_res, units_com, units_mixed. We will keep these for now as we continue exploring.
  • in Socioeconomic category, all attributes are related to Census Tract, we will set them aside for now as we continue exploring.

Now dropping select entries with missing data:

Getting Building Geographic Coordinate

In order to be able to plot these landmarks buildings accurately on map, we need to use their corrosponding longitude and latitude coordinates. The dataset doesn't come with buildings' coordinates, so we will have to get the coordinates based on their street addresses.

⭐ Next Steps:

  • We will need find a way to get geographic coordinated for all landmarks. There should be related dataset or API we can utilize from the City of Boston. Worst case scenario, we will use street address to inference respective coordinates.

Additional Dataset¶

Boston Landmarks Commission: List of All Submitted Petitions & Status

The Boston Landmarks Commission (BLC) maintains a live list of all the petitions of with their status, whether they are pending, approved, or denied. This dataset would give us a better understanding about Boston's landmarks - we want to look at those that are still pending, and those were denied.

Convert Address to Latitude Longitude¶

Operations for Boston Building Dataset:

  • Convert entries in zipcode field from 4 digits to 5 digits, simply adding 0 at the front
  • Convert all AV in st_name_suf to AVE for address-to-coordiantes conversion accuracy
  • Aggregate address related fields into one single full address field

# Install and Import Geopy Package

from geopy.geocoders import Nominatim
import time
In [ ]:
geolocator = Nominatim(user_agent = "BostonLandmarkCoordinates")
In [ ]:
total_addresses = len(cleaned_filtered_df['full_address'])
processed_count = 0

for index, row in cleaned_filtered_df.iterrows():
    address = row['full_address']
    try:
        location = geolocator.geocode(address, timeout=10)
        if location:
            cleaned_filtered_df.at[index, 'lat'] = location.latitude
            cleaned_filtered_df.at[index, 'lon'] = location.longitude
            cleaned_filtered_df.at[index, 'coordinate'] = f"{location.latitude}, {location.longitude}"
        else:
            cleaned_filtered_df.at[index, 'lat'] = None
            cleaned_filtered_df.at[index, 'lon'] = None
            cleaned_filtered_df.at[index, 'coordinate'] = None
    except Exception as e:
            cleaned_filtered_df.at[index, 'lat'] = None
            cleaned_filtered_df.at[index, 'lon'] = None
            cleaned_filtered_df.at[index, 'coordinate'] = None
    finally:
        processed_count += 1
        print(f"\r{processed_count} out of {total_addresses} processed...{address} ==> {cleaned_filtered_df.at[index, 'coordinate']}", end="", flush=True)
        time.sleep(1)

print("\nDone.")

Visualization Schematic¶

Interactive Map with 4 Layers:

  • Actual Landmarks: Historical Register Layer
  • Would-Be Landmarks: Pending Status Layer
  • Could've-Been Landmarks: Rejected Petition Layer
  • Your Landmarks: Interactive Community Layer. Allows museum visitors to add their personal landmarks to the map, democratizing the concept of landmarks and acknowledging the significance of everyday locations.

Plus, a flow chart shows how to a landmark becomes a landmark.
